1
00:00:01,035 --> 00:00:03,913
Seven years ago,
I was recruited to work for SD-6,

2
00:00:03,996 --> 00:00:06,749
which I was told
was a covert branch of the CIA.

3
00:00:06,832 --> 00:00:10,461
I was trained as a spy,
warned not to tell anyone what I did.

4
00:00:10,544 --> 00:00:12,922
I thought I was working
for the good guys

5
00:00:13,005 --> 00:00:16,508
until I told my fiancé about SD-6,
and they had him killed.

6
00:00:16,592 --> 00:00:18,552
That's when I learned the truth,

7
00:00:18,636 --> 00:00:21,805
that SD-6 is part of the enemy
I thought I was fighting.

8
00:00:21,889 --> 00:00:25,976
Now, I'm a double agent, working
with the real CIA to bring down SD-6.

9
00:00:26,060 --> 00:00:30,981
My only ally is another double agent,
a man I hardly know. My father.

10
00:00:33,525 --> 00:00:37,029
It seems that during the Cold War,
six nuclear weapons

11
00:00:37,112 --> 00:00:39,531
were smuggled into
the United States.

12
00:00:39,615 --> 00:00:43,160
When SD-6 picked up our nuke,
it went on a plane bound for Egypt.

13
00:00:43,244 --> 00:00:46,288
- What?
- They sold the thing to Hassan.

14
00:00:46,372 --> 00:00:49,875
- You're going to Cairo.
- Yeah. I need your help.

15
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,545
SD-6 can't know I'm there.

16
00:01:02,596 --> 00:01:04,682
I'm holding the core.

17
00:01:15,859 --> 00:01:21,073
I'm holding enough plutonium
to liquefy our insides in 48 hours.

18
00:01:21,156 --> 00:01:23,450
Put it down.

19
00:01:23,534 --> 00:01:26,412
- I put it down, you'll kill me.
- Now.

20
00:01:26,495 --> 00:01:28,622
I'm going to count to one.

21
00:01:30,207 --> 00:01:32,084
OK.

22
00:01:47,266 --> 00:01:49,143
You're falling behind, Sydney.

23
00:01:51,312 --> 00:01:53,647
And I don't accept late papers.

24
00:01:53,731 --> 00:01:56,650
OK, you know what?
Good point, you shouldn't,

25
00:01:56,734 --> 00:01:59,445
but I do have a really good excuse.

26
00:01:59,528 --> 00:02:03,616
OK. I was on a business trip
and my flight was delayed.

27
00:02:05,743 --> 00:02:08,412
I have the ball
and I'm ready for instruction!

28
00:02:08,495 --> 00:02:11,207
- ETA two minutes.
- I might not have two minutes!

29
00:02:11,290 --> 00:02:13,918
If you recall,
I made it clear in my syllabus

30
00:02:14,001 --> 00:02:16,086
I would receive papers via email

31
00:02:16,170 --> 00:02:18,255
if you can't get them to me directly.

32
00:02:18,339 --> 00:02:21,884
- You have email, don't you?
- Yes. You're not gonna believe this,

33
00:02:21,967 --> 00:02:25,679
but there was a blackout
where I was staying.

34
00:02:25,763 --> 00:02:27,056
Honestly.

35
00:02:35,231 --> 00:02:38,609
OK, stop.
I can appreciate the complexities

36
00:02:38,692 --> 00:02:41,528
of pursuing a degree
with a full-time job,

37
00:02:41,612 --> 00:02:45,491
but it seems your work is taking
precedence over your education.

38
00:02:45,574 --> 00:02:48,953
Now, admit it, Sydney.
You're dropping the ball.

39
00:03:05,177 --> 00:03:07,805
My job is a means to an end.

40
00:03:08,639 --> 00:03:11,100
And your class makes me feel like

41
00:03:11,183 --> 00:03:14,853
maybe, someday, I'll be able
to do something more with my life.

42
00:03:22,861 --> 00:03:24,863
Alright.

43
00:03:24,947 --> 00:03:27,992
Next paper's due Thursday.
That won't be a problem?

44
00:03:28,075 --> 00:03:30,953
No, not at all. Thank you so much.

45
00:03:38,294 --> 00:03:40,546
Are you sure about that?

46
00:03:44,258 --> 00:03:46,343
How's Friday?

47
00:04:15,331 --> 00:04:17,833
It's confusing.
Charlie has an amazing offer

48
00:04:17,917 --> 00:04:19,418
from Flemming-Letterman.

49
00:04:19,501 --> 00:04:22,213
It's the most prestigious law firm
in LA.

50
00:04:22,296 --> 00:04:24,798
- But Charlie's not excited?
- He's gone weird.

51
00:04:24,882 --> 00:04:27,760
He never wants to talk about it,
he doesn't brag.

52
00:04:27,843 --> 00:04:29,011
Wouldn't you brag?

53
00:04:29,094 --> 00:04:32,389
I would be non-stop talking
about myself if they wanted me.

54
00:04:32,848 --> 00:04:35,976
You and Charlie
come from different places.

55
00:04:36,060 --> 00:04:39,813
In his whole family,
he's first-generation college.

56
00:04:39,897 --> 00:04:42,024
- True.
- Not to mention law school.

57
00:04:42,107 --> 00:04:44,985
He's probably nervous.
He's probably terrified.

58
00:04:45,069 --> 00:04:48,572
I called my dad last night
to ask him what he thought

59
00:04:48,656 --> 00:04:50,658
and he said, "Give it a rest."

60
00:04:50,741 --> 00:04:53,369
"Charlie is one of the good ones."

61
00:04:53,452 --> 00:04:56,205
- He's right.
- It's weird having the feeling

62
00:04:56,288 --> 00:04:59,124
that someone you love
isn't telling you everything.

63
00:05:01,126 --> 00:05:05,548
I can't believe you call your dad
for advice. I just can't imagine.

64
00:05:05,631 --> 00:05:08,384
The worst
is having a dad who is always right.

65
00:05:08,467 --> 00:05:11,178
No, it's not the worst thing.

66
00:05:14,056 --> 00:05:17,518
I ran into my father... last week.

67
00:05:17,601 --> 00:05:19,812
- Where?
- Just...

68
00:05:19,895 --> 00:05:21,897
Just out shopping.

69
00:05:21,981 --> 00:05:23,732
It was... It was so empty.

70
00:05:23,816 --> 00:05:26,110
It wasn't empty.
It was full, actually.

71
00:05:26,193 --> 00:05:29,321
Full of awkwardness
and lame pauses and...

72
00:05:29,405 --> 00:05:30,823
I don't know.

73
00:05:30,906 --> 00:05:33,284
Your dad, you know, he's just...

74
00:05:35,119 --> 00:05:37,204
He's just your dad.

75
00:05:38,247 --> 00:05:41,625
I don't want it to be like that
any more. I'm sick of it.

76
00:05:42,418 --> 00:05:46,547
I mean, I always had this feeling
that maybe, someday,

77
00:05:46,630 --> 00:05:50,634
I don't know,
my dad and I would connect,

78
00:05:50,718 --> 00:05:54,430
and that things
could start to get better.

79
00:05:54,513 --> 00:05:56,515
You know my opinion of your dad.

80
00:05:57,433 --> 00:05:58,893
I know.

81
00:05:58,976 --> 00:06:01,312
But if you can find it in your heart

82
00:06:01,395 --> 00:06:04,398
to forgive him for being
who he's been all your life,

83
00:06:04,481 --> 00:06:07,359
which I would find impossible
and could never do,

84
00:06:07,443 --> 00:06:09,695
then you should make a real effort.

85
00:06:09,778 --> 00:06:11,864
How do you start something that?

86
00:06:11,947 --> 00:06:14,158
I have so many questions, I just...

87
00:06:14,241 --> 00:06:15,618
You can call the man.

88
00:06:15,701 --> 00:06:18,204
I won't reconnect with him
on the phone.

89
00:06:18,287 --> 00:06:22,791
Go to his work. Go to the aeroplane
factory and just start talking.

90
00:06:24,210 --> 00:06:26,003
You're really good at talking.

91
00:06:35,554 --> 00:06:36,680
Dad?

92
00:06:37,556 --> 00:06:39,516
Sydney, what are you doing here?

93
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:41,769
I would've called.
I didn't know if...

94
00:06:41,852 --> 00:06:43,646
You shouldn't be here.

95
00:06:43,729 --> 00:06:46,607
I told you
I have a thousand questions.

96
00:06:46,690 --> 00:06:48,692
They're keeping me awake at night.

97
00:06:48,776 --> 00:06:50,903
Then take something.

98
00:06:50,986 --> 00:06:54,156
Did you know SD-6
was gonna recruit me? Did you help?

99
00:06:54,240 --> 00:06:57,076
- This isn't the time.
- I need to ask about Mom.

100
00:06:57,159 --> 00:06:59,912
- Sydney...
- Was it just an accident,

101
00:06:59,995 --> 00:07:04,250
or did you tell her about what
you were doing, like I told Danny?

102
00:07:04,333 --> 00:07:06,961
Look where you are. You're exposed.

103
00:07:07,044 --> 00:07:08,587
Dad, please.

104
00:07:08,671 --> 00:07:11,131
Don't come here again. Not again.

105
00:07:18,013 --> 00:07:21,141
The device that you withdrew
from Taipei last month

106
00:07:21,225 --> 00:07:22,768
remains in Analysis.

107
00:07:22,851 --> 00:07:26,397
We're trying to figure out
what it does and how it does it.

108
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:30,109
At the time, I told you
that Oskar Müller was the designer.

109
00:07:30,192 --> 00:07:33,362
The truth,
Müller was just an academic,

110
00:07:33,445 --> 00:07:36,407
a scientist
who took another man's sketches,

111
00:07:36,490 --> 00:07:40,244
translated them into construction
plans and put it together.

112
00:07:40,327 --> 00:07:43,789
- So, who designed it?
- A man named Milo Rambaldi.

113
00:07:43,873 --> 00:07:47,167
- Never heard of him.
- That doesn't surprise me.

114
00:07:47,251 --> 00:07:49,253
He died in 1496.

115
00:07:49,336 --> 00:07:52,840
Rambaldi was Pope Alexander VI's
chief architect.

116
00:07:52,923 --> 00:07:56,427
Excommunicated for heresy,
sentenced to death

117
00:07:56,510 --> 00:08:01,056
for suggesting that someday science
would allow us to know God.

118
00:08:02,266 --> 00:08:04,977
After his death,
his workshop was torn apart.

119
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:09,106
His plans and sketches were traded
and sold for next to nothing.

120
00:08:09,189 --> 00:08:13,527
In the next five centuries, his work
was scattered throughout the world.

121
00:08:13,611 --> 00:08:15,362
No one is sure what's left.

122
00:08:15,446 --> 00:08:18,032
Which is unfortunate
because, last March,

123
00:08:18,115 --> 00:08:22,119
a Russian historian happened upon
one of Rambaldi's early designs.

124
00:08:22,203 --> 00:08:28,250
She recognised something
that looked a lot like a transistor.

125
00:08:28,334 --> 00:08:31,420
I don't understand.
Do you understand?

126
00:08:31,503 --> 00:08:34,256
It seems that Rambaldi
was a prophet.

127
00:08:35,257 --> 00:08:39,428
We acquired one of his notebooks
from San Lazzaro.

128
00:08:40,471 --> 00:08:42,473
This is the analysis report.

129
00:08:45,726 --> 00:08:49,605
Rudimentary schematic for
a transportable vocal communicator.

130
00:08:49,688 --> 00:08:53,525
He was designing a cellphone around
the time of the Ottoman Empire.

131
00:08:53,609 --> 00:08:55,611
- Come on!
- Ridiculous, right?

132
00:08:55,694 --> 00:08:58,531
You know me.
I'm not a New Age kind of guy.

133
00:08:58,614 --> 00:09:01,242
I don't believe
in the power of the pyramid.

134
00:09:01,325 --> 00:09:02,868
I'm not a big granola fan.

135
00:09:02,952 --> 00:09:05,579
This stuff
typically makes me roll my eyes,

136
00:09:05,663 --> 00:09:08,332
and then my eyes came across this.

137
00:09:08,415 --> 00:09:10,709
Written in 1489.

138
00:09:10,793 --> 00:09:12,836
Rambaldi wrote machine code?

139
00:09:12,920 --> 00:09:15,965
If I could,
it's probably not machine code.

140
00:09:16,048 --> 00:09:20,261
The concept of zero has been
around... Well, it precedes Christ.

141
00:09:20,344 --> 00:09:23,013
The numeral one
has been around even longer.

142
00:09:23,097 --> 00:09:25,307
Ptolemy used zeroes as punctuation.

143
00:09:25,391 --> 00:09:29,436
In Indian text, zero is more of
a spiritual concept than a number.

144
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:32,648
When I say Indian,
I don't mean bows and arrows and -

145
00:09:32,731 --> 00:09:34,942
Thank you, Marshall.

146
00:09:35,901 --> 00:09:39,196
We don't know what it is.
Rambaldi has become a priority.

147
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:42,116
We want to learn what it is
before anybody else.

148
00:09:42,199 --> 00:09:45,035
- Have you run the sequence?
- It's incomplete.

149
00:09:45,119 --> 00:09:48,914
The sequence was written on
the back of two Rambaldi sketches.

150
00:09:48,998 --> 00:09:52,793
We possess one. The other
is in this man's private collection.

151
00:09:52,877 --> 00:09:57,172
Eduardo Benegas, Spanish VC.
Auto enthusiast.

152
00:09:57,256 --> 00:10:02,052
He also owns the largest collection
of pornographic art in Madrid.

153
00:10:02,761 --> 00:10:06,140
Which I thought
was an interesting fact. Sorry.

154
00:10:06,223 --> 00:10:10,311
We negotiated to buy one of the
sketches and he withdrew the piece.

155
00:10:10,394 --> 00:10:13,230
We believe he was tipped off
as to its real value.

156
00:10:13,314 --> 00:10:17,401
We think it's K-Directorate.
They're on to Rambaldi too.

157
00:10:17,484 --> 00:10:21,071
It's possible K-Directorate
stole a key from Benegas.

158
00:10:21,155 --> 00:10:25,534
Our data-reconnoissance division
thinks, although it hasn't confirmed,

159
00:10:25,618 --> 00:10:28,787
that he's surrounded at all times
by six bodyguards.

160
00:10:28,871 --> 00:10:32,374
We're talking about guys trained
under UEl Special Forces.

161
00:10:32,458 --> 00:10:34,418
We also have reason to believe

162
00:10:34,501 --> 00:10:37,630
that Benegas keeps the key
on his person at all times.

163
00:10:37,713 --> 00:10:41,884
So the big question is,
how did K-Directorate swipe the key?

164
00:10:41,967 --> 00:10:44,470
Anna.

165
00:10:45,095 --> 00:10:46,931
It was Anna, wasn't it?

166
00:10:55,522 --> 00:11:00,236
Eduardo Benegas has a sketch
drawn by Milo Rambaldi.

167
00:11:04,031 --> 00:11:06,742
There's a code written on the back.

168
00:11:09,370 --> 00:11:11,455
SD-6 wants that code.

169
00:11:13,374 --> 00:11:15,459
The sketch is in a case.

170
00:11:17,711 --> 00:11:19,797
The case is in a vault.

171
00:11:20,839 --> 00:11:25,094
The vault is on the top floor
of a car museum owned by Benegas.

172
00:11:26,512 --> 00:11:28,597
So I'm going to Madrid.

173
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:31,725
What's my counter mission?

174
00:11:32,977 --> 00:11:35,604
So it's 2,000 words or less

175
00:11:35,688 --> 00:11:39,024
on gene sequencing
in virus-resisting cabbage.

176
00:11:39,108 --> 00:11:41,402
And I'm realising slowly that

177
00:11:41,485 --> 00:11:43,904
I might not
have a real handle on it.

178
00:11:43,988 --> 00:11:45,656
Which part?

179
00:11:45,739 --> 00:11:48,576
Just the part
about the gene sequencing

180
00:11:48,659 --> 00:11:51,412
and the virus-resistant cabbage.

181
00:11:51,495 --> 00:11:55,207
Doesn't your paper have
a science correspondent? Hello?

182
00:11:55,875 --> 00:11:57,376
Hi.

183
00:11:59,420 --> 00:12:02,298
OK. Yeah.

184
00:12:03,591 --> 00:12:05,593
- Hello?
- OK, thanks.

185
00:12:05,676 --> 00:12:08,470
- I will come by.
- Sorry, man. Wrong number.

186
00:12:08,554 --> 00:12:10,556
So you're busy.

187
00:12:10,639 --> 00:12:13,309
You OK? You looked like...

188
00:12:13,392 --> 00:12:16,687
It was Danny's landlord.
They found some of his stuff.

189
00:12:16,770 --> 00:12:18,814
- You alright?
- Yeah, yeah.

190
00:12:18,898 --> 00:12:22,109
D'you want me to...
I can get that stuff, bring it back.

191
00:12:22,192 --> 00:12:25,571
Would you mind? It's just
I have to go to San Diego tonight.

192
00:12:25,654 --> 00:12:28,157
Yeah, don't worry about it.
It's done.

193
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:30,075
Thanks.

194
00:12:31,076 --> 00:12:34,455
- So, who called?
- It was a wrong number.

195
00:12:34,538 --> 00:12:36,707
They were looking for a pizza place.

196
00:12:39,418 --> 00:12:43,255
I think I'm gonna go for a quick run
before my cab comes.

197
00:12:48,093 --> 00:12:50,262
- Hey.
- Hi.

198
00:12:50,346 --> 00:12:53,515
Devlin wants you to follow through
on Sloane's orders.

199
00:12:53,599 --> 00:12:55,893
We're both after
the same missing code.

200
00:12:55,976 --> 00:12:57,686
- You're kidding me?
- No.

201
00:12:57,770 --> 00:13:01,815
- You knew about Rambaldi?
- I didn't. The agency did.

202
00:13:01,899 --> 00:13:04,526
Da Vinci meets Nostradamus.
I don't buy it.

203
00:13:04,610 --> 00:13:07,863
Tell the CIA chief in Barcelona
to prep for a dead drop.

204
00:13:07,947 --> 00:13:11,784
Worst case, I'll encrypt the code on
an MP3 and leave it on Audiogalaxy.

205
00:13:11,867 --> 00:13:14,370
How'd the Russians
find out about Rambaldi?

206
00:13:14,453 --> 00:13:16,580
You're the Intel guy.

207
00:13:17,414 --> 00:13:20,501
What can you tell me
about this woman, Anna Espinosa?

208
00:13:24,797 --> 00:13:26,966
Born in Cuba, raised in Russia.

209
00:13:27,049 --> 00:13:29,051
One of the last Cold War babies.

210
00:13:29,134 --> 00:13:33,597
Go-to officer at K-Directorate
for wet work and active measures.

211
00:13:33,681 --> 00:13:36,809
A year ago, I met
with an informant in Yugoslavia.

212
00:13:36,892 --> 00:13:39,687
Just a guy with Intel
who needed the money.

213
00:13:39,770 --> 00:13:43,816
Anna recorded the conversation with
a mic from the building next door.

214
00:13:43,899 --> 00:13:46,318
How do you know?

215
00:13:46,402 --> 00:13:48,612
Because as I shook his hand to leave,

216
00:13:48,696 --> 00:13:52,324
she blew out his brains,
even though she got what she wanted.

217
00:13:52,408 --> 00:13:55,452
Her way of telling me
I was out of my league.

218
00:13:57,329 --> 00:14:01,125
- Be careful out there.
- I'll see you when I get back.

219
00:14:01,917 --> 00:14:04,003
No, actually, you won't.

220
00:14:05,045 --> 00:14:06,922
I'm being replaced by a senior.

221
00:14:07,006 --> 00:14:10,634
I wasn't experienced enough
to be your handler.

222
00:14:15,890 --> 00:14:17,975
It was really good to meet you.

223
00:14:19,018 --> 00:14:21,103
Good luck in Madrid.

224
00:14:23,731 --> 00:14:26,191
He's an idiot!
I mean, that's the problem.

225
00:14:26,275 --> 00:14:29,570
So is Davenport.
They're so involved in their own...

226
00:14:29,653 --> 00:14:31,822
- Protocol.
- Know who's replacing me?

227
00:14:31,906 --> 00:14:33,324
- Lambert.
- Lambert?

228
00:14:33,407 --> 00:14:36,660
Can I say something?
And not just as a fellow officer,

229
00:14:36,744 --> 00:14:39,121
but as a very smart man.

230
00:14:39,205 --> 00:14:41,165
- What?
- You're too emotional.

231
00:14:41,248 --> 00:14:43,959
- Not again.
- You're attached to this woman.

232
00:14:44,043 --> 00:14:47,046
- It's your answer for everything.
- If I analysed you...

233
00:14:47,129 --> 00:14:49,924
- Shut up, stop it!
- I'd say maybe you're jealous.

234
00:14:50,007 --> 00:14:53,761
Of Lambert? Gimme a break!
He may be senior, but he's junior.

235
00:14:53,844 --> 00:14:56,222
Now he can see Sydney
and you're crazy.

236
00:14:56,305 --> 00:14:58,265
- This is not about me!
- It is.

237
00:14:58,349 --> 00:15:00,267
No, it's not!

238
00:15:10,778 --> 00:15:12,446
She's going to Madrid.

239
00:15:12,530 --> 00:15:16,200
There's another agent with
K-Directorate who is dangerous.

240
00:15:16,825 --> 00:15:18,953
